# Branching and Git Workflow

Branch names, PR rules, merge process, release branches.

_Document for **{{COMPANY_NAME}}** (`{{COMPANY_SLUG}}`). Last updated **{{CURRENT_DATE}}**._

## Branching, commits and pull requests

The default branch is `main`. Feature work lives on a short-lived branch named `<initials>/<topic>`. Pull requests target `main` directly; we do not maintain a separate develop branch.

Commits follow the Conventional Commits convention. Every pull request has at least one reviewer who is not the author; review is for correctness, security and clarity, in that order. Failed CI blocks merge.

## Testing

Three layers, each with a clear remit. **Unit tests** prove the smallest unit of behaviour is correct. **Integration tests** prove a package collaborates with its real dependencies (database, file system, child processes). **End-to-end tests** prove the whole product still works.

Coverage is reported but not the headline metric. The headline metric is whether the test that would have caught the bug exists. When a bug is found the fix lands together with the test that would have caught it.

## Deployment

We deploy via the platform named in the *Deployment Guide*. Every deployment is triggered by a tag on `main`; we do not deploy from a feature branch.

Rollbacks are a one-command operation; the command and the rollback triggers are recorded in the *Deployment Guide*. The on-call engineer is responsible for executing them when the *Incident Response Plan* triggers.

